observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE: 

(42)30. Require the Municipal Treasurer/Supply Office to keep and maintain PCs;

(43)31. Order the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of PPEs, and to prepare and submit the RPCPPE; and

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the:
Municipal Accountant to:
submit the liquidation reports and supporting documents of the 53 cash advances amounting to ₱19,859,277.00;
simultaneously submit the related accounts of reported liquidations of cash advances together with the submission of the CDJ and GJ to COA;
The Municipal Treasurer to send proof of submission of liquidation report to the Audit Team and moving forward to liquidate cash advances for:
Salaries, Wages, etc. – within five (5) days after each end of the month pay period;
Petty Operating Expenses and Field Operating Expenses within twenty (20) days after the end of the year; subject to replenishment as frequently as necessary during the year.
Concerned personnel to send proof of submission of liquidation report to the audit team and moving forward to liquidate cash advances for official travel within thirty (30) days after return to his permanent official

We recommended, and Management agreed, that the Municipal Mayor require the:
MDRRMO to:
ensure proper monitoring on the utilization of LDRRMF and immediately communicate PPAs that are in need of funding;
refrain from adjustment of appropriation per PPA in the LDRRMFIP without legal basis or authority through enactment of ordinance by the Local Sanggunian;
Municipal Budget Officer to:
ensure all disbursement are in accordance with the approved Annual Budget together with the LDRRMFIP and strictly monitor the availability of appropriation before the approval of an obligation;
support any changes in the LDRRMFIP with augmentation, re-alignment, or supplemental budget, if any;
prepare and maintain separate RAAOs for QRF, MOOE, and CO, in relation to the approved LDRRMFIP;
Municipal Accountant to:
effect the necessary entries for the transfer of unspent balance and adjust the balance of Trust Liabilities-DRRM account at year-end;
provide appropriate disclosure on the LDRRMF balance to the Notes to Financial Statements; and
require the Municipal Treasurer to cause the complete transfer of unexpended balances of CY 2023 and 2024 LDRRMF to the Trust Fund account.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive direct the:
Municipal Treasurer to:
Refrain from dispensing cash to co-employees or to elected officials for the payment of Job Orders;
Release payments only to the payee or his duly authorized representative;
Require authorization letter from the claimant indicating the particulars of the amount to be claimed on the payee’s behalf;
Municipal Accountant to:
Require complete documentation upon grant and liquidation of cash advances for payment of Job Order personnel.

(3) a. Formulate plans and strategize the complete conduct of physical count of all its PPE, and prepared and submit the RPCPPE not later than January 31 of the ensuing year in compliance with Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
(4) b. Attach the required property stickers for PPE with the required number format under COA Circular No. 2020-06 in order to have a uniform property identification system
(5) We further recommended that the Municipal Accountant and the Property Custodian prepare and maintain the PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, in order to facilitate the periodic reconciliation if the PPE accounts with results of the physical inventory taking.

We recommended and the management agreed that the LCE require the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Make necessary adjustments to arrive at the correct balances of the affected accounts in the financial statements;
b. Verify the validity of the accounts payable balance aged two years and more; and adjust the ₱2,000.00 arising from error in payment. Valid claims shall be paid. Otherwise, cause the reversion of the payables to the unappropriated surplus of the general fund.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:
a. Direct the Municipal Assessor to provide the Assessment Roll to the Municipal Accountant;
b. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to provide the Municipal Accountant the following: (a) Updated Real Property Tax Account Register and (b) Taxpayer’s Index Card and Certified List of Taxpayer’s showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to set up the required RPT and SET Receivable for the year 2022 and appropriate amount of receivables for the prior years;
d. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to immediately send collection letters of the delinquent LGU Officials and provide a copy of their payments to this Office;
We likewise recommended that the legislative officials, in consultation with the MT and other concerned officials draw up plans to strategize and strengthen collection drive beyond the required posting and sending of notices.
Moreover, we also recommended that the management should intensify the collections of the real property and special education taxes, and avail of the remedies for the collection of the real property tax.

We recommended, and Management agreed, that the LCE require:
a. The Budget Officer (MBO) to prepare separate registries for LDRRMF- QRF; LDRRMF- MOOE and LDRRMF- CO;
b. The MBO and MDRRMO to stop charging ineligible expenses to the LDRRMF; 
c. Municipal Accountant to set up and maintain subsidiary ledgers for the STF for unutilized DRRMF by year of transfer, receipts of NDRRMF by transferring agency, DRRMF from other LGUs by LGU, and other sources by the donor to readily determine the balances of transfers/receipts; and correct the Notes to Financial Statements by reflecting the complete disclosure of balances for current and STF by year end.
Moving forward, we likewise recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the strict observance of the accounting and reporting guidelines for the LDRRMF as enunciated under COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012.
